b'HI! I\xe2\x80\x99m Sof\xc3\xada Hern\xc3\xa1ndez, a human rights activist and Political Science student from Costa Rica who will be taking over Levi\xe2\x80\x99s Instagram stories today to tell you all about my experiences of being an activist in Costa Rica and working alongside movements like, @fridaysforfuture_costarica.
\xc2\xa0
Living in Costa Rica has shown me the effects of climate change first hand. Right now we are in an environmental crisis due to recent hurricanes.\xc2\xa0
\xc2\xa0
Costa Rica\xc2\xa0has been\xc2\xa0recognized as a world leader in human rights and environmental conservation,\xc2\xa0but\xc2\xa0 we have a long way to go to protect our lands from climate change and pollution and to promote environmental justice.\xc2\xa0
\xc2\xa0
Climate Justice is Social Justice;\xc2\xa0keeping the two at the center of the debate\xc2\xa0is the only way to address the\xc2\xa0environmental crisis\xc2\xa0we are facing.\xc2\xa0I believe\xc2\xa0the future of humanity needs to be based on sustainability and human rights. Thank you so much for following along today and be sure to follow along on my journey @greenysofi.'

b'When creating the VOTE PSA, Oge Egbuonu thought about what the fight for social justice could look like in addition to the traditional ways of organizing. Realizing that the arts is the ladder to the soul, Oge utilized this collective space of unlearning and re-educating ourselves to inspire the masses through this poetic art piece.

To that end, @OgeTheYogi creatively brought this campaign to life by creating and directing a PSA set to artist @SignedJayMarie \xe2\x80\x99s poem about the importance of Voting in this election.

Tomorrow is the most important election of our lifetime, please utilize one of the many tools we have and Vote.'

b'Oge Egbuonu
Activist, Creative and Filmmaker

\xe2\x80\x9cRepresentative John Lewis said in his final published piece, \xe2\x80\x98The vote is the most powerful nonviolent change agent you have in a democratic society.\xe2\x80\x99 Reading that hit me at my core because one\xe2\x80\x99s voice is extremely powerful and necessary to reimagining a world that chooses equity and care over oppression and exploitation, and one way to utilize one\xe2\x80\x99s voice is to vote. So on Tuesday, November 3, activate your voice, activate your vote...see you at the polls.\xe2\x80\x9d
.
Photography by: @djenebaaduayom
Styling by:\xc2\xa0@ecduzit
Make-up by:\xc2\xa0@tobyfleischman'

b"Kahlila Williams 
Student & Activist

\xe2\x80\x9cVoting is important to me because it is an opportunity to get our voices heard and be a part of the change that affects our lives. This is the one time of year that we can decide on everyday issues like healthcare, education, housing, and global issues. This year has brought so much awareness to issues within our nation that many have failed to address. Throughout 2020 we have seen Black and Brown people disportionately killed by this pandemic and by law enforcement, an awareness of racism that needed to be addressed for years. 2020 has brought history making movements and were only halfway through, but we don't have to stop there. We know that change is possible because we have seen change in policies, Juneteenth recognized by many as a national holiday, and many calling for the defending or the police.For many generations people have struggled to win the right to vote and many countries are still fighting. You have seen the inequality in our nation so use YOUR voice, this is YOUR opportunity.\xe2\x80\x9d
.
Photography by: @djenebaaduayom
Styling by:\xc2\xa0@ecduzit
Make-up by:\xc2\xa0@tobyfleischman"

b"Ross Butler

\xe2\x80\x9cOne thing I can say about the 2020 election is that voting now has this spirit of rebellion, a rebellion against the status quo and to make our want for change heard. b'Brandon Flynn 
Actor & Activist 

"Voting, to me, when everyone can vote fairly, is a clear example of our potential Freedom as Americans. It is a way to have our voices heard as a collective, it is a way to inspire and be a part of change. Each vote counts, even down to the Electoral College, it is our individual voices that make the difference. We have responsibilities as members of a Country to vote for our liberties and how the systems we live in function. Importantly, too, voting on a local level helps ensure that our voices and our belief systems are being looked after, supported and lifted. By electing our local Judges, DA officials, etc.; WE make this happen. 
 
As many of us are sitting at home wondering if another stimulus check will come, if $1200 is a defining number of our worth, as people are sick and dying and COVID-19 cases rise, as many of us are beginning to wake up to the systemic racism we operate within, the level of white supremacy that runs rampant in our government, our wallets, and our current administration\xe2\x80\xa6we can only move towards a gradual progression in the other direction, a direction in a system that reflects a world that a community can imagine, a much more beautiful and caring world. My vote this election is my commitment to fighting for better options on the 2024 ballot, it is my commitment to fighting for my marginalized neighbors lives, it is a commitment to fight for human rights to not be a discussion that needs to be voted on, but something that is agreed as a given and essential in opening the doors to a future of possibilities and improvements that we are too blind to see now. Voting is about putting our worth out there, defining it for ourselves together, and letting a system know that we are here, we won\xe2\x80\x99t settle, we have rights, and we will fight."
.
Photography by: @djenebaaduayom
Styling by:\xc2\xa0@ecduzit'

b'Dr. Safiya Noble 
Scholar, Professor, & Author

\xe2\x80\x9cNot one single person can afford to sit out this election. We need to be educated and strategic about the candidates and issues when we cast our ballots, too. Trust the civic, activist, and community groups that matter to you to get informed about the issues\xe2\x80\x94don\xe2\x80\x99t just rely on search engines and social media, which will be flooded with disinformation and untruths to confuse voters. Think critically and vote powerfully.

The trajectory of the most pressing issues in society\xe2\x80\x94from racial justice to employment and worker\xe2\x80\x99s rights, from affordable health care to climate change and the future of civil rights\xe2\x80\x94these issues will hinge on national, state, and local elections in 2020. 

I will be voting on behalf of Breonna Taylor in 2020, and for a world where Black Lives Matter, where working people matter, where LGBTQIA+ lives matter, and where people and the planet are prioritized before a profit-at-all-cost culture of greed and heartlessness. With so much at stake, we must do whatever it takes to secure a future where everyone is included and injustice is not the norm. 

On November 3rd, let\xe2\x80\x99s show up and show out.\xe2\x80\x9d
.
Photography by: @djenebaaduayom
Styling by:\xc2\xa0@ecduzit
Make-up by:\xc2\xa0@tobyfleischman'

b"Rorri Burton
ASL Interpreter

\xe2\x80\x9cGenerations of\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0Black people before me fought for the right to learn how to read, to go to school, to be treated and recognized as fully human, and for the right to vote.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0How dare I spit in the face of those ancestors who were ostracized, brutalized and murdered, by squandering that right and not voting - not just voting for who becomes president, but at the state and local levels, as well.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0I will not spit in the faces of John Lewis and C.T. Vivian, Ida B. Wells and Ella Baker by allowing my vote to go uncast.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0Don't let racism and oppression profit from your apathy.\xe2\x80\x9d
.

b'George Floyd\xe2\x80\x99s death at the hands of Minneapolis police exposed systemic failures that define Black American life \xe2\x80\x94 not just in policing, but in representation, opportunity and power. These failures reach and shape every corner and conference room in the United States, including those at Levi Strauss & Co.

We must eradicate the racial inequality at the heart of Levi Strauss & Co. We must build a company worthy of everyone who works here. Starting today, we must begin to live our values.

b'June 19 is better known as Juneteenth, a holiday that commemorates the ending of slavery in the United States in 1865. As we look at the state of our nation, we as a company recognize the significance of this date and honor what it meant for this country then and now. To mark this celebration of freedom, we will be continuing our #UseYourVoice Live series to hear from Black community members on their personal experiences and the ways in which change can happen, if and when we all get involved. \nFor the first time, we will observe Juneteenth as a company-wide holiday, and are encouraging employees to take the day to further educate themselves. Tune in with us on June 19th 2020, for a special JUNETEENTH episode of Use Your Voice Live on Instagram.'
